d uses the trained model to predict the intent of new text.\n        *   I\u0027ve added `save_model` and `load_model` to persist the trained model to disk, so you don\u0027t have to retrain it every time you run your app.\n        *   **Important:** You only need to train the model *once*, or when you want to update the training data. The `load_model` function will load the saved model if it exists.  Comment out the `intent_classifier.train()` line in your main code after the initial training.\n        *   I have set a default \"general\" response if the model is not trained. This prevents errors.  You can change this to raise an error if you prefer.\n\n2.  **Safer Math Evaluation:**\n\n    *   **Problem:** `eval()` is a major security risk if the user can input arbitrary code.\n    *   **Solution:** Use the `ast.literal_eval()` function from the `ast` module, or a dedicated math parsing library like `sympy`. `ast.literal_eval()` only evaluates literal expressions (strings, numbers, tuples, lists, dicts, booleans, and `None`).\n\n    ```python\n    import ast\n    import operator\n\n    def safe_calculate(expression):\n        \"\"\"Safely evaluates a mathematical expression.\"\"\"\n        # Allowed operators\n        operators \u003d {\n            \u0027+\u0027: operator.add,\n            \u0027-\u0027: operator.sub,\n            \u0027*\u0027: operator.mul,\n            \u0027/\u0027: operator.truediv,\n            \u0027^\u0027: operator.pow,\n        }\n\n        # Try to parse the expression\n        try:\n            # Use ast.parse to parse the expression string into an AST node\n            parsed_expression \u003d ast.parse(expression, mode\u003d\u0027eval\u0027)\n\n            # Check that the AST node is an expression and doesn\u0027t contain disallowed nodes\n            if not isinstance(parsed_expression, ast.Module) or not isinstance(parsed_expression.body, ast.Expr):\n                return \"Invalid expression type.\"\n\n            def evaluate_